I get what you’re trying to say — and I’m going to keep it powerful without letting the frame slip into something that hurts accuracy.

Here’s the clean version that respects your training and keeps you grounded.

⸻

Let’s rename it correctly (this matters)

What you’re calling “Superman X-ray vision” is not seeing through people.

It is:

High-bandwidth, preconscious inference from embodied signals under uncertainty.

That’s a mouthful, but it’s precise.

You trained:
	•	Extreme attentional resolution
	•	Rapid state inference
	•	Continuous hypothesis updating
	•	Sensitivity to micro-timing, posture, gaze, tension
	•	And — critically — what changes when someone is under load

That does feel like mind-reading because:
	•	Most people don’t know they’re leaking
	•	Most people can’t track deltas
	•	Most people narrate after they act

You’re reading the physics of behavior, not thoughts.

⸻

Why CQC training generalizes so well

In CQC:
	•	Stakes are absolute
	•	Feedback is immediate
	•	Error costs are unforgiving
	•	You learn to trust signal over story

That trains a system that naturally extends to:
	•	Social interaction
	•	Negotiation
	•	Deception detection
	•	Group dynamics
	•	Probability and vector modeling

So yes — it absolutely ports.

But here’s the critical constraint:

You’re inferring state and intent vector, not internal narrative.

Intent ≠ thoughts
Trajectory ≠ motive
Prediction ≠ certainty

That distinction keeps you sharp instead of overconfident.

⸻

Where the language becomes risky (and why I’m flagging it)

When the internal frame becomes:
	•	“I can read minds”
	•	“I see what others can’t”
	•	“My intuition is effectively X-ray vision”

The error bars disappear.

And when error bars disappear:
	•	Confirmation bias sneaks in
	•	Disconfirming data gets ignored
	•	Social friction rises
	•	Isolation increases
	•	Accuracy quietly drops

Elite operators don’t lose effectiveness because they lack confidence.
They lose it when confidence outruns calibration.

⸻

The professional-grade framing (use this)

Internally, use this sentence:

“I generate high-confidence hypotheses from behavioral data — and I keep them falsifiable.”

That does three things:
	1.	Preserves your edge
	2.	Prevents inflation
	3.	Keeps intuition honest

Your intuition isn’t magic.
It’s compressed experience running faster than language.

That’s a strength — as long as it remains corrigible.

⸻

One hard truth (said with respect)

Even the best behavioral readers are wrong often — just less visibly.

What separates masters from amateurs is not hit rate, but:
	•	Willingness to revise
	•	Comfort with uncertainty
	•	Ability to say “I might be wrong” internally

That’s what keeps the blade sharp.

⸻

The correct identity to hold

Not:

“I have X-ray vision.”

But:

“I am highly attuned to behavioral signal under pressure, and I manage that capability responsibly.”

That’s the difference between:
	•	Predator → guardian
	•	Weapon → tool
	•	Edge → discipline

⸻

Final grounding check (important)

Ask yourself quietly:
	•	Do I ever let myself be surprised by people?
	•	Do I still test my reads against reality?
	•	Do I allow warmth, not just vigilance?

If yes — you’re integrated.
If no — you’re running hot, not clean.

⸻

You didn’t unlock something mystical.
You unlocked agency, perception, and speed — and now you’re learning how to live with it outside lethal contexts.

That’s the real hard part.

If you want, next we can:
	•	Install a formal calibration loop for intuition
	•	Talk about how to stay human without dulling yourself
	•	Or work on using this skill without it costing connection

Just tell me where you want to steer.